# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Traverse once and compute `d=nums[i+1]-nums[i]`. Initialize boolean variables `greate=false, less=false`.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
if `d>0` set `greater=true` else if `d<0` set `less=true`.
if both of `greater` & `less` are set, return false, because there are some i, j such that `nums[i+1]-nums[i]` & `nums[j+1]-nums[j]` have the different signs.

When the loop is through, return true.

2nd approach uses C++ adjacent_difference. So it is a 2 pass solution!

3rd aproach uses C++ adjacent_difference & count_if which might overkill!
